# Ways of Working: {{ display_name }}

## Delivery Standards

- Keep pull requests narrow and vertically sliced
- Every feature ships with tests at the right level, not just implementation code
- Architecture decisions that change package boundaries or infrastructure choices get an ADR
- Prefer boring, explicit Spring configuration over clever meta-programming

## Coding Conventions

- Controllers are thin and usually delegate to exactly one service method
- Request DTOs use Bean Validation annotations and are separate from persistence entities
- Service methods are named after business use cases, not framework actions
- Repository interfaces expose domain-oriented methods such as `findActiveSubscriptionByAccountId`
- Avoid field injection and framework static access; use constructor injection everywhere

## Package Discipline

{% if use_ddd %}
- Keep the domain model free from controller and transport concerns
- Do not let JPA-specific annotations or repository APIs leak into the conceptual domain layer without a deliberate reason
- Cross-context orchestration belongs in application services, not entities
{% else %}
- Domain classes may use JPA annotations, but transport DTOs still stay out of the persistence model
- If a service grows beyond a coherent use case boundary, split it by workflow rather than by technical helper methods
- Shared utility packages are a last resort; prefer placing logic close to the feature that owns it
{% endif %}

## Testing Rules

{% if test_strategy == "junit-only" %}
- Pure business logic gets plain JUnit tests with minimal Spring context usage
- Use Spring slice tests only where framework integration adds real value
- Mock repositories and external clients carefully; do not mock the method under test's own behavior
{% elif test_strategy == "junit-and-testcontainers" %}
- Unit tests cover business branching and validation rules
- Integration tests use Testcontainers for database-backed repositories and key infrastructure adapters
- Do not replace the real database with H2 for repository semantics that rely on vendor behavior
{% else %}
- Unit tests cover pure logic
- Slice tests verify MVC/WebFlux behavior, serialization, and validation
- Integration tests verify database and messaging wiring
- End-to-end smoke tests cover the highest-value user or system journeys only
{% endif %}

## Commands

{% if build_tool == "maven" %}
```bash
./mvnw test
./mvnw verify
./mvnw spring-boot:run
```
{% else %}
```bash
./gradlew test
./gradlew check
./gradlew bootRun
```
{% endif %}

## Dependency Hygiene

- Add Spring starters only when they materially reduce custom boilerplate
- Avoid overlapping libraries that solve the same problem
- Prefer Spring Boot auto-configuration when it remains understandable; override explicitly when behavior matters
- Document any non-standard infrastructure dependency in `docs/architecture.md` or an ADR

## Database and Migrations

- Migration files are reviewed like code
- Repository methods must reflect actual query intent
- Large read queries should use projection DTOs or dedicated read models
- Transaction boundaries live in services, not in controllers

## Security and Operations

- New endpoints require an explicit authn/authz decision before merge
- Sensitive configuration is provided via environment-specific secrets
- Logs must be structured and scrubbed of secrets, tokens, and raw personal data
- Operational runbooks belong in docs when the application introduces non-trivial infrastructure
